00:01:06.310 --> 00:01:11.450 position:56%
&gt;&gt; In 1978, a joint
congressional resolution established

00:01:11.450 --> 00:01:15.010
Asian-Pacific-American
Heritage Week.

00:01:15.010 --> 00:01:19.610
The first 10 days of May
were chosen to coincide

00:01:19.610 --> 00:01:25.510
with two major milestones in
Asian Pacific American history.

00:01:25.510 --> 00:01:30.210
May 7th, 1843, which
marked the arrival

00:01:30.210 --> 00:01:37.280 position:56%
of the first Japanese immigrants in
the Unites States, and May 10, 1869,

00:01:37.280 --> 00:01:41.030
the completion date of the
Transcontinental Railroad,

00:01:41.030 --> 00:01:44.180
upon which many Chinese
workers labored.

00:01:44.180 --> 00:01:48.360
In 1992, Congress expanded
the observance

00:01:48.360 --> 00:01:53.960
into a month-long celebration
now known as the Asian American

00:01:53.960 --> 00:01:57.590 position:56%
and Pacific Islander Heritage Month.

00:01:57.590 --> 00:02:01.750
This year the White House has
once again issued a presidential

00:02:01.750 --> 00:02:05.140
proclamation designating May

00:02:05.140 --> 00:02:10.080
as Asian Pacific American Heritage
Month, acknowledging the men

00:02:10.080 --> 00:02:15.440
and women of Asian and
Pacific ancestry who continue

00:02:15.440 --> 00:02:20.350
to make many important
contributions to our nation.

00:02:20.350 --> 00:02:26.660
This year's theme is "Unite Our
Voices by Speaking Together."

00:02:26.660 --> 00:02:32.770
This theme encourages the various
AAPI communities to join together

00:02:32.770 --> 00:02:39.310
to honor and acknowledge
heritage, self and community

00:02:39.310 --> 00:02:41.530
and to celebrate diversity.

00:02:41.530 --> 00:02:48.310
The AAPI experience varies greatly,
and all groups must join together

00:02:48.310 --> 00:02:52.660
to communicate our
individual experiences.

00:02:52.660 --> 00:02:57.600
Diversity is a journey, and
we cannot travel there alone.

00:02:57.600 --> 00:03:03.470
By uniting our voices we can
raise issues and tell stories

00:03:03.470 --> 00:03:07.350
that elevate the AAPI community.

00:03:07.350 --> 00:03:11.930
With this theme we hope to improve
representation in the workplace

00:03:11.930 --> 00:03:16.700
by communicating the benefits
of a diverse workforce.

00:03:16.700 --> 00:03:20.560
Today's program draws on
our diversity of experience

00:03:20.560 --> 00:03:24.800
and illustrates the
principle of inclusion

00:03:24.800 --> 00:03:28.710
that enriches our understanding
of the world.

00:03:28.710 --> 00:03:31.910
So here to introduce
our featured speaker,

00:03:31.910 --> 00:03:36.000
please welcome the Librarian
of Congress, Dr. Carla Hayden.

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:47.760
[applause]

00:03:47.760 --> 00:03:52.660
&gt;&gt; CARLA HAYDEN: Thank you for
inviting me here to be part

00:03:52.660 --> 00:03:55.100
of the event and for the sponsors.

00:03:55.100 --> 00:04:03.070
I'm honored to be in a different
position of introducing the person

00:04:03.070 --> 00:04:11.900
who usually makes sure that
my introductions are accurate,

00:04:11.900 --> 00:04:13.900
and has been a part

00:04:13.900 --> 00:04:18.870
of my professional
journey for quite a while.

00:04:18.870 --> 00:04:22.290
Someone said, "Do you
need a lot of notes

00:04:22.290 --> 00:04:24.750
and things about Roswell Encina?"

00:04:24.750 --> 00:04:27.420
I said, "I don't think so."

00:04:27.420 --> 00:04:33.360
But you have, in your
program, his curriculum vita.

00:04:33.360 --> 00:04:40.350
You have his resume, and you see
he had a distinguished career

00:04:40.350 --> 00:04:45.980
in journalism, and was a person
who was asking the questions,

00:04:45.980 --> 00:04:50.230
who was right on the scene
in so many instances.

00:04:50.230 --> 00:04:56.580
When the Enoch Pratt Free
Library was looking for someone

00:04:56.580 --> 00:05:01.170
to tell the library's story,
to help us shape our message

00:05:01.170 --> 00:05:05.590
at a pretty difficult time
in the library's history.

00:05:05.590 --> 00:05:12.010
We were looking for that person
who would guide me as the CEO,

00:05:12.010 --> 00:05:18.390 position:56%
and who would guide the entire staff
and bring a sense of unity and sense

00:05:18.390 --> 00:05:21.140
of purpose to what we were doing.

00:05:21.140 --> 00:05:23.750
We knew what we were doing,
and that we had that purpose,

00:05:23.750 --> 00:05:28.600
but we wanted to communicate
it and bring people in.

00:05:28.600 --> 00:05:33.160
Roswell Encina was the
person that was chosen.

00:05:33.160 --> 00:05:38.810
And I asked him, I said, "You're
going from getting the news

00:05:38.810 --> 00:05:42.200
to making the news and what
is it about public service,"

00:05:42.200 --> 00:05:49.740 position:56%
because it was entering a different
arena, "that attracted you to this?"

00:05:49.740 --> 00:05:53.780
And he said, "I want
to tell good stories.

00:05:53.780 --> 00:06:01.450
I want to bring out the positive
aspects of what everyone is doing

00:06:01.450 --> 00:06:04.070
and what the human
experience can be,"

00:06:04.070 --> 00:06:07.180
and that's what cinched it for us.

00:06:07.180 --> 00:06:10.700
The other part, personally
and professionally as someone

00:06:10.700 --> 00:06:15.760
who was leading this effort
that I needed, was a no-man,

00:06:15.760 --> 00:06:20.130
an N-O man, not a yes person.

00:06:20.130 --> 00:06:24.560
You can find a lot of people
who'll say, "Yes, it's great

00:06:24.560 --> 00:06:27.770
and you just go and do it.

00:06:27.770 --> 00:06:35.370
That was a great speech, and you
look great today, you just wow."

00:06:35.370 --> 00:06:41.110
I wanted, and the reason why I have
him here with me on the journey

00:06:41.110 --> 00:06:43.970
at the Library of Congress
was I needed someone

00:06:43.970 --> 00:06:47.480
that would literally go, "No.

00:06:47.480 --> 00:06:54.200
No. You're going to wear that?

00:06:54.200 --> 00:06:56.890
Oh, don't say that.

00:06:56.890 --> 00:07:03.530
No." I needed someone that would
have the strength of conviction,

00:07:03.530 --> 00:07:08.390
the courage to look me in
the face and say, "No."

00:07:08.390 --> 00:07:11.810
That's the most important thing,
that trust, that confidence,

00:07:11.810 --> 00:07:16.720
and that's why I am more than
pleased and honored to bring

00:07:16.720 --> 00:07:19.160
to this stage the Library

00:07:19.160 --> 00:07:24.440
of Congress' No-man,
Mr. Roswell Encina.

00:07:24.440 --> 00:07:34.460
[applause]

00:07:34.460 --> 00:07:35.760
&gt;&gt; ROSWELL ENCINA: Oh, boy.

00:07:35.760 --> 00:07:37.060
Here we go.

00:07:37.060 --> 00:07:38.360
Good afternoon to everyone.

00:07:38.360 --> 00:07:39.660
I want to thank Dr.
Hayden, of course,

00:07:39.660 --> 00:07:40.960
and Robert for being
here this afternoon, and,

00:07:40.960 --> 00:07:42.760
of course, for introducing me.

00:07:42.760 --> 00:07:44.060
Usually it's the other way around.

00:07:44.060 --> 00:07:47.010
As she says, I'm the one who's
usually, regularly introducing her

00:07:47.010 --> 00:07:49.670
to come up to the stage, so it's
a little weird doing it the other

00:07:49.670 --> 00:07:50.970
way around.

00:07:50.970 --> 00:07:53.460
I also want to thank her
for allowing me to be part

00:07:53.460 --> 00:07:55.960
of this journey here to
the Library of Congress.

00:07:55.960 --> 00:07:59.450
When friends still ask me to this
